    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-03-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-03-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="325"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                <head>325. National Security Decision Memorandum 99<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d325fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1"
                            >RG</gloss> 59, <gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss> Files: Lot 83 D 305,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> 99. Secret. Copies were sent to
                        the Secretary of the Treasury, the President of the Export-Import Bank, the
                        Director of <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>, the Chairman of <gloss
                            target="#t_CEA1">CEA</gloss>, the Chairman of the <gloss
                            target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, the Director of Central Intelligence,
                            <persName corresp="#p_PPG1">Peter Peterson</persName>, and Clark
                        MacGregor.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-03-01">March 1, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Commerce</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>East-West Trade</item>
                </list>
                <p>In response to the recent memoranda from the Secretaries of State, Defense and
                    Commerce on possible measures to increase U.S. trade with Eastern Europe and the
                    Soviet Union,<note n="2" xml:id="d325fn2">Presumably <ref target="#d314"
                            >Documents 314</ref>–<ref target="#d316">316</ref> and <ref
                            target="#d321">321</ref>. According to a January 27 memorandum from
                        Veliotes to Irwin, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>
                        had sent a memorandum to the President on October 22, 1970, recommending
                        modifications in the U.S. posture vis-à-vis trade with Communist countries.
                        Veliotes wrote that no response to this proposal nor to related <gloss
                            target="#t_USC1">USC</gloss> initiatives on relaxation of trade controls
                        with respect to Yugoslavia and Romania had been received. (National
                        Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, <gloss target="#t_SS1"
                            >S/S</gloss> Files: Lot 74 D 164, <persName corresp="#p_IJNII1"
                            >Irwin</persName>/<persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>
                        Meetings 1970-1972) <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>’ October
                        22, 1970, memorandum has not been found.</note> the President has decided to
                    defer any decision on new Administration initiatives to liberalize U.S. trade
                    policy toward the Communist countries in regard to most-favored-nation tariff
                    treatment or Export-Import Bank transactions. The President has also decided,
                    however, that Congressional initiatives in these areas should be opposed only in
                    a very low key way.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
